  <TEXT>
    <Tag>TXT_KEY_UNIT_MOUNTED_SERGEANT_PEDIA</Tag>
    <English>[TAB]A sergeant, or rather serjeant in medieval Europe, was a man of lesser rank and wealth to a knight, but with comparable equipment and training. Serjeants could fight either as heavy or light cavalry, and here fulfill that secondary role. Serjeants ranked above the common man-at-arms on the social scale. Although the social structure of the Norman society of England was generally static, the easiest manner for a man to attain social rank and improve his standing was through military service, as the Norman states, unlike the Germanic ones, believed in knighting men of common birth who demonstrated nobility and courage on the field.</English>
