  <TEXT>
    <Tag>TXT_KEY_UNIT_COGGE_PEDIA</Tag>
    <English>[TAB]The cog (or cogge) was a type of ship which first appeared in Northern Europe and was widely used from the 12th century onwards. Cogs were generally made of oak, an abundant timber in the Baltic region, and were fitted with a single mast and square-rigged sail. Even though this rigging prevented them sailing into the wind, cogs between associated with sea going trade in the northern waters of Medieval Europe. They were generally flat-bottomed and employed a stern-mounted rudder with fore and stern castles as defense against pirates, enabling them to often used as warships. By the late 15th century they were replaced by the carrack which was more sea-worthy and suitable for sailing in the open ocean over longer distances.</English>
