  <TEXT>
    <Tag>TXT_KEY_UNIT_GUN_GALLEY_PEDIA</Tag>
    <English>[TAB]A galley is a type of ship that can be propelled entirely by human oarsmen and used for warfare and trade, but usually had masts and sails for use when the wind was favourable. Various types of galleys dominated naval warfare in the Meditteranean Sea from the 8th century BC to the 16th century. Many medieval states, notably Venice, Genoa, the Byzantines, Arabs and the Ottoman Turks depended largely on heavily-armed galleys until the introduction of the ocean-going "man-of-war". The Battle of Lepanto, in 1571, was one of the largest and last sea battles in which galleys played the principal part.[PARAGRAPH:2]Galleys remained in regular use in the Meditteranean until the introduction of broadside sailing ships in the 17th century. While war galleys originally carried archers and slingers for offensive operations and defence, the advent of gunpowder weapons saw the development of early cannons mounted on ships. In fact, medieval war galleys pioneered the use of naval guns, with the typical Venetian gun galley or "laterna" mounting high calibe guns in the bow and stern with various lighter swivel guns deployed throughout the ship. However, with the development of the high-sided carrack and galleass capable of powerful broadside cannonfire, the usefulness of these gun galleys eventually came to an end.</English>
